<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910313-0039</DOCNO><DOCID>910313-0039.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Union Carbide Corp.:   Chemical Plant in Texas   Closed Following Explosion</HL><DATE>03/13/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   UK</CO><IN>CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)</IN><LP>   Union Carbide Corp.'s Seadrift facility in Port Lavaca,Texas, was shut down yesterday by an early-morning explosion.   Union Carbide said the blast, which hospitalized threeplant employees, &quot;apparently took place in equipment used inthe manufacture of ethylene oxide,&quot; which is used to makeantifreeze, polyester fibers and other products.</LP><TEXT>   More than a dozen other people were treated at nearbyhospitals and released, including two people who were drivingon a public road near the plant when the 1:18 a.m. blast tookplace.   The Danbury, Conn., company couldn't immediately provideadditional details on the cause of the incident, but it saidit doesn't believe the chemical-plant explosion produced anyharmful emissions.   Union Carbide couldn't say how long it expects the bigplant will be closed. The plant is responsible for aboutone-third of the chemical and plastics manufacturer'sethylene-oxide production, and about two-thirds of itspolyethylene production.</TEXT></DOC>